Certainly! Below is the TikZ LaTeX code to generate a 2D projection of the polytope \( P_1 \) corresponding to \(\mathbb{P}^2\) with vertices \( v_1 = (1,0) \), \( v_2 = (0,1) \), and \( v_3 = (-1,-1) \):

```latex
\documentclass[tikz]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]

% Define the vertices
\coordinate (v1) at (1,0);
\coordinate (v2) at (0,1);
\coordinate (v3) at (-1,-1);

% Draw the edges
\draw[-Stealth] (v1) -- (v2) node[midway, above right] {$e_{12}$};
\draw[-Stealth] (v2) -- (v3) node[midway, below left] {$e_{23}$};
\draw[-Stealth] (v3) -- (v1) node[midway, below right] {$e_{31}$};

% Label the vertices
\node[above right] at (v1) {$(1,0)$};
\node[left] at (v2) {$(0,1)$};
\node[right] at (v3) {(-1,-1)};

% Draw the axes
\draw[->] (-1.5,0) -- (1.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
\draw[->] (0,-1.5) -- (0,1.5) node[above] {$y$};

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will produce a 2D plot of the polytope \( P_1 \) with the specified vertices and edges. The `scale` option adjusts the size of the drawing for better visibility. Adjustments can be made as needed.

